title: Vendor Invoice/Purchase Order Spreadsheet - Whittier CA Police

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Vendor Invoice/Purchase Order Spreadsheet - Whittier CA Police
communications.communication:
Hello:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any spreadsheet or list maintained by the WPD showing all invoices and purchase orders submitted by or paid to vendors.  If such a spreadsheet can be produced from the Department’s accounting software showing amount of payment, date of payment, payee, and description of reason for payment, then I am requesting that spreadsheet.   Please cover a period going back to 2012.  

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

*The requested documents will be made available to the general public via Muckrock, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am a published citizen-journalist with articles in the Long Beach Beachcomber and on FORTHE.org. My research has been featured by the Los Angeles Times, Long Beach Post, Knock-LA, and other local publications.

Sincerely,

Gregory Buhl
lead researcher at CheckLBPD.org

communications.subject: City of Whittier - Public Records Extension Request
communications.communication:
Good evening Mr. Buhl,

In response to your California Public Records Act (CPRA) request dated March 21, 2024, regarding "any spreadsheet or list maintained by the WPD showing all invoices and purchase orders submitted by or paid to vendors. If such a spreadsheet can be produced from the Department's accounting software showing amount of payment, date of payment, payee, and description of reason for payment, then I am requesting that spreadsheet. Please cover a period going back to 2012," the City Clerk Department has compiled the following response:

California Government Code Section 7922.535 requires the City to provide a response to your request within 10 days of receipt indicating what, if any, of the documents sought will be disclosed. Government Code Section 7922.535 also permits the City to extend the period in which it responds to your request by an additional 14 days, if necessary. The City is requesting an extension because the City needs to compile and filter the data generated from a voluminous report through our financial software. As an example, the reports for FY 2022-23 and 2023-24 produced an excess of 1400 pages that need to be converted to excel and then filtered by department.  Once the records have been gathered, there will also be an examination to determine if any of the records are exempt from disclosure. A determination regarding your request will be sent to you no later than April 12, 2024, which is 14 days from the tenth day following the City's receipt of your request.

In the event the documents are collected and examined, and a determination on their disclosure is made prior to that time, we will provide you with that determination sooner. If you have any questions, please contact the City Clerk Department at (562) 567-9850.

title: Federal Marshal Operation on Jan 5, 2022 at Playa Palms Apartments (Department of Justice, United States Marshals)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Federal Marshal Operation on Jan 5, 2022 at Playa Palms Apartments (Department of Justice, United States Marshals)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

On January 5th, 2022 twenty or more armed US Marshals were present at the Playa Palms Apartments from approximately 9:00 am to 9:00 pm.  Along with 3 mobile command centers and numerous state, local, and county law enforcement officers.  Please disclose all documents pertaining to this operation.  Playa Palms Apartments is located at 2200 W San Angelo St, Gilbert AZ, 85233.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Victor Montoya

title: ATL 311 Records Request: 225 Rogers St NE (Pullman Yards)

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: ATL 311 Records Request: 225 Rogers St NE (Pullman Yards)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

List of any ATL 311 case related to the following search terms:
- Location: 225 Rogers St NE
- Property Owner: Atomic Entertainment
- Property/Business Name - any of: "Pratt Pullman", "Pullman Yards", "Pullman"

I would like to understand what metadata is available for ATL 311 cases.  To achieve that, I would like the following information:
- INFORMATION_SCHEMA.COLUMNS, filtered to table(s) that contain ATL 311 cases
- Data Dictionary (i.e. column descriptions + context on what they're used for)

Until I have the above metadata, I'm not sure what is available for 311 cases, so here is a list of fields I need:
- Creation Date (when the ATL 311 request was submitted)
- Request Description
- Location (feel free to provide whatever fields apply to this: cross-streets, address, lat/lon, etc)
- Case #
- Disposition (acknowledged, rejected...whatever final state the case ended up in)

Time range: 2017 through present day (March 31, 2024)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brent Brewington

title: Department of Defense support for "My Christmas Hero" (2023)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Department of Defense support for "My Christmas Hero" (2023)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to collaboration between the Department of Defense (DoD) and the production of the 2023 movie "My Christmas Hero," directed by Martin Wood and starring Candace Cameron Bure. I request any and all documents pertaining to DoD support for "My Christmas Hero." Such documents may include but should not be limited to: script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of the DoD and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "My Christmas Hero," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Board Chair Emails in February, 2024
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

A log of all emails to/from the CPS Board Chair, from February 01, 2024 to February 29, 2024.

communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
April 2, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 159582-57380573@requests.muckrock.com RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N014947-030324 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: A log of all emails to/from the CPS Board Chair, from February 01, 2024 to February 29, 2024. 

1. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Under the rules of FOIA, private information and unique identifiers contained within public records are exempt from public disclosure; those portions have been redacted including personal email addresses and other highly personal information. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Personally identifiable student record information has been redacted in accordance with the Illinois School Student Records Act 105 ILCS 10/1 et seq. and the corresponding Section 7.5(r) FOIA exemption (5 ILCS 140/7.5(r)). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(f) which exempts from release “[p]reliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body. The exemption provided in this paragraph (f) extends to all those records of officers and agencies of the General Assembly that pertain to the preparation of legislative authority.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f). Furthermore, this exemption is “intended to protect the communications process and encourage frank and open discussion among agency employees before a decision is made." State Journal-Register v. Univ. of Ill. Springfield, 994 N.E.2d 705, 713 (2013). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(m) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[c]ommunications between a public body and an attorney [] representing the public body that would not be subject to discovery in litigation, and materials prepared or compiled by or for a public body in anticipation of a criminal, civil, or administrative proceeding upon the request of an attorney advising the public body.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(m). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(p) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[r]ecords relating to collective negotiating matters between public bodies and their employees or representatives, except that any final contract or agreement shall be subject to inspection and copying.” 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(p). To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

--- Please respond above this line --- 
April 2, 2024 Miriam Bhimani 159554-50654449@requests.muckrock.com 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N014931-022924 
Dear Ms. Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request seeking the following information: Records sufficient to show the following: 

1. Contents of emails and attachments highlighted on attached email log released via FOIA N014773-020124. RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Under the rules of FOIA, private information and unique identifiers contained within public records are exempt from public disclosure; those portions have been redacted including race/ethnicity, cell phone numbers, personal email addresses, and other highly personal information. Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Further, redactions were applied to mask communications between a parent and their child’s school district pursuant to section 7(1)(c). Parents have a personal privacy interest under 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c) in their identifying information when they contact their child’s school to express opinions. (See Ill. Att' y Gen. PAC Req. Rev. Ltr. 38873, issued June 30, 2016, at 4-5 and Ill. Att' y Gen. PAC Req. Rev. Ltr. 56488). Personally identifiable student record information has been redacted in accordance with the Illinois School Student Records Act 105 ILCS 10/1 et seq. and the corresponding Section 7.5(r) FOIA exemption (5 ILCS 140/7.5(r)). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(f) which exempts from release “[p]reliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body. The exemption provided in this paragraph (f) extends to all those records of officers and agencies of the General Assembly that pertain to the preparation of legislative authority.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f). Furthermore, this exemption is “intended to protect the communications process and encourage frank and open discussion among agency employees before a decision is made." State Journal-Register v. Univ. of Ill. Springfield, 994 N.E.2d 705, 713 (2013). Course materials or research materials used by faculty members have been redacted pursuant to section (j)(iv) of the FOIA. 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(j)(iv). Redactions have been applied pursuant to Section 7.5(h) of the FOIA, which exempts from disclosure “information the disclosure of which is exempted under the State Officials and Employees Ethics Act, and records of any lawfully created State or local inspector general’s office that would be exempt if created or obtained by an Executive Inspector General’s office.” 5 ILCS 140/7.5(h). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(m) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[c]ommunications between a public body and an attorney [] representing the public body that would not be subject to discovery in litigation, and materials prepared or compiled by or for a public body in anticipation of a criminal, civil, or administrative proceeding upon the request of an attorney advising the public body.” 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(m). Redactions have been made pursuant to section 7(1)(p) of the FOIA which exempts from release “[r]ecords relating to collective negotiating matters between public bodies and their employees or representatives, except that any final contract or agreement shall be subject to inspection and copying.” 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(p). Finally, please note that records that do not pertain to the transaction of public business have been withheld from release. To the extent you consider this a denial, pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a) you may file a Request for Review with the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at: Public Access Counselor; Office of the Attorney General; 500 South 2nd Street; Springfield, IL 62706.  You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court; 5 ILCS 140/11. If you have any questions, please contact our office at (773) 553-3500. Thank you for your request. Sincerely, Annie Righi Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

• The city department for which the request was intended
• A description of the requested records
• The tracking number assigned by this office to the request
• The date on which the request was closed by this office
• The final disposition of the request, including, if possible, whether the request was fully fulfilled, partially fulfilled, rejected in its entirety, resulted in no responsive documents, or remains open

• The number of released pages

Please provide the responsive materials in the form of a spreadsheet (either in CSV or XLS file formats), if possible.

Please contact me if your office has any questions about this request. 

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

communications.subject: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Agency Roster (Yuma County Sheriff's Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Please provide an electronic copy of your agency's Policy & Procedures and Complaint Form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Marcus Boyd

In response to your request for public records, a copy of the complaint form can be located at https://www.yumacountysheriff.org/help-complaint.htm. Attached is a copy of policies and procedures manual.

Are you asking for any research documents produced by a contractor? If so, then there are only 2 contractors who would have produced anything along those lines: ICF and STPI. Additionally, NASA, not OSTP maintains ICF contracts.

Let  us know if you have any other question.

Thank you!

Regards,

OSTP FOIA Team

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Records sufficient to show copies of Parent Restriction letters issued from July 1, 2022 - June 30, 2023 for the following schools/instances:

BEARD
BEAUBIEN
BELDING
BRIDGE

RESPONSE: The CPS FOIA Office has reviewed your request and has determined the following: In response to number 1 of your request, the FOIA Office has conducted a due diligence search for records responsive to your request and has determined that no records responsive to your request were located. 
In response to number 2 of your request, the letters that the FOIA Office was able to locate are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. 
Please be advised that certain student and parent/guardian information was redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(j)(iii) exempts from release information concerning a school or university’s adjudication of student disciplinary cases, but only to the extent that disclosure would unavoidably reveal the identity of the student. 
Section 7(1)(c) exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subject of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. 
You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

title: K9 usage in Fitchburg Public Schools (Fitchburg Police Department)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: K9 usage in Fitchburg Public Schools (Fitchburg Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

For ANY AND ALL canine use within the Fitchburg Public Schools between August 1, 2018 to the date of receipt of this FOIA request, please provide:

    1) the DATES, TIMES, AND DURATION of the canine use; and
    2) LOCATION of the canine use, as specific as possible (for example, if a canine search was limited to a bathroom then the school and room number; or if a canine search was performed on all lockers but did not extend into any classroom, then that should be noted); and
    3) the REASON(S) for the use; and
    4) the LEGAL JUSTIFICATION for the reason(s) for the use, citing statute and/or case law if possible; and
    5) the NAME OF THE POLICE DEPARTMENT(S) involved in the canine use, including but not limited to any police department present during the canine use even if that police department was not the owner or handler of the canine(s); and
    6) if the canine(s) is owned by a police department, the NAME(S) AND BADGE/ID NUMBER(S) of the canine(s) involved; and 
    7) if the canine(s) is NOT owned by a police department, the name(s) of the canine(s) involved, and the name, address, phone number, and email of the OWNER of the canine(s); and 
    8) if the canine(s) is NOT owned by a police department, the name(s) of the HANDLER(S) of the canine(s); and 
    9) if the canine(s) is NOT owned by a police department, any and all contracts, memorandum of understanding, memorandum of agreement, and any other official contract concerning the canine(s) and police department requesting the canine(s) use; and
    10) THE NAME(S) AND BADGE NUMBER(S) of the police department employee(s) involved; and the name(s) of the Fitchburg Public School ADMINISTRATOR(S) AND OTHER EMPLOYEES in charge of the canine use, including but not limited to any school employee who made the request, directly monitored the canine usage, or who otherwise acted as a school representative concerning the canine use; and
    11) any and all RESULTS of the canine use, including but not limited to non-productive searches; and
    12) if the canine use was requested or required by the Fitchburg Public Schools, the name of the Fitchburg Public School employee REQUESTOR(S); and
    13) if the canine use requested or required by the Fitchburg Police Department, the name of the Fitchburg Police Department employee REQUESTOR(S).

The term "canine" is intended to mean a police-owned or police-commissioned dog that is utilized for searches or other police functions within schools. Police functions also includes but is not limited to:
- searches
- demonstrations
- teaching
- training
- any other ancillary police function
as long as the canine use was performed in the Fitchburg Public School, on Fitchburg Public School owned property, and/or requested by the Fitchburg Public Schools.

The interest of this FOIA request is for the records produced or maintained by each department (for example, the Fitchburg Public School district, or the Fitchburg Police Department, and not simply one school within the system or one police building). Therefore this information must be from each department's records, and not coordinated with any other department, entity, agency, or group, unless that outside department's normally stores or maintains records for that department. For example, the school can provide a police report which the school has on file prior to this public records request, but should not request a police report from a police department solely in order to fulfill this public records request.

Fees for public records requests are defined in part in Massachusetts law 950 CMR 32.07 (2)(m) for municipal records and 950 CMR 32 (2) in general.

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, processed by a representative of the news media/press and is made in the process of news gathering and not for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Neal Delfeld

Good afternoon,

As the designated Records Access Officer for the Fitchburg Police Department I have been tasked with responding your recent request for public records.

Today I received an email  in regards to a Public Records Request that was originally dated February 23, 2020  It appears that the original request was sent to the email address infor@fitchburgpolice.com<mailto:infor@fitchburgpolice.com>.

The above email address is not an active email address. After reviewing the specifics in this records request, this is the same data that was requested with the same language in February 10th of 2020. This request was answered by Captain Giannini on February 17, 2020

Captain Giannini responded with the data including several attachments. Included in this email are copies of the data submitted in the response along with copies of the emails outlining the communication.

The email chain below articulates the response.

Should you require any additional data or documents please reach out.

Please be advised that pursuant to 950 CMR 32.00 and G.L. Chapter 66, Section 10A(a) you have the right to appeal this decision to the Supervisor of Records, at the address listed below, within 90 days from your original request.  The appeal must include your original request along with this response.  Pursuant to G.L. Chapter 66, Section 10A(c) you also have the right to seek judicial review by commencing a civil action in the Superior Court.
Supervisor of Records

Office of the Secretary of the Commonwealth
McCormack Building, Room 1719
One Ashburton Place
Boston, MA 02108

I kindly request that you send me a return email acknowledging this response to your public records request.

Respectfully

All contracts, acquisition agreements, memoranda of understanding, and any other agreements signed between:

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Chris Gelardi

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request #NYSP-23-12-1041
communications.communication:
Dear FOIL Appeals Officer:

This is an appeal of FOIL NYSP-23-12-1041, completed on March 5, 2024, which yielded 53 pages of records. Specifically, this is an appeal of the redactions found on pages 18, 47, 52, and 53 of that package of yielded records.

The New York State Police redacted the documents based on Public Officers Law §87(2)(b) ("personal privacy"); §87(2)(d) ("trade secrets ... the disclosure of which would cause substantial injury to the competitive position of the vendor"); and §87(2)(d) ("intra-agency material").

Regarding §87(2)(d): The New York state Committee on Open Government, citing the United States Supreme Court (Kewanee Oil Co. v. Bicron Corp., 1973), has repeatedly made clear: "Trade secrets" refer only to actual secrets, "and must not be of public knowledge or of a general knowledge in the trade or business." (See the attached example COG advisory opinion.)

But in its redactions of pages 18, 47, 52, and 53 of the yielded documents, the New York State Police seem to have redacted any and all information related to a product it procurred from Cobwebs America, Inc. in November 2023, including the names of the products procurred.

As such, I request that a FOIL appeals officer review the redactions on pages 18, 47, 52, and 53, and re-produce the documents with only information related to actual trade secrets redacted.

Thank you for your time. Please feel free to email me at chris@nysfocus.com or call (419) 309-6331 if you have any questions.

Sincerely,
Chris Gelardi

title: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (Secretary Of State Florida)

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (Secretary Of State Florida)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on local ballot initiatives/referenda that took place in the state since 1972. Specifically, I need the following information to be included in the data.

1. Text of the ballot initiative/referendum
2. Local government where the election took place.
3. County where the local government is located
4. Election date
5. Result of election (votes for, votes against, pass/fail)
6. Threshold to pass (50%, two-thirds, etc)

This website from California provides a good example of the type of data I am requesting:
https://data.ca.gov/dataset/election-data/resource/67e83a65-2b55-41ec-9420-b33b666d4711

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Jimin Han

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (Secretary Of State Florida)
communications.communication:
Dear Jimin,

Thank you for contacting the Department of State. The Division of Elections provides online election results<https://results.elections.myflorida.com/> from 1978 forward. These election results include county level results on constitutional amendments. They do not include the results of local level initiatives or referendums.

The State Archives of Florida holds Series S 1258 (Election Return Canvasses, 1865-2004<http://archivescatalog.info.florida.gov/default.asp?IDCFile=/fsa/DETAILSS.IDC,SPECIFIC=505,DATABASE=SERIES,> which contains county level initiative and referendum results. The results from 1972 - 2004 are contained within approximately 39 volumes. The Archives staff has estimated 2 hours of research per volume to fulfill your request. This estimate includes the time that it takes to locate each volume, identify the appropriate pages, and then scan the appropriate pages from each volume. Because the Archives staff is limited to 90 minutes for remote research requests, we would suggest that you visit the Archives to conduct your research. The plan your visit page<https://dos.fl.gov/library-archives/archives/visit/> has details regarding in-person research; if you are not able to travel to the State Archives in Tallahassee, you may consider hiring the services of a private researcher. The attachment contains a list of researchers who requested their names be placed on a list maintained by the State Library and Archives of Florida. Please note, this list is merely an aid to our patrons and is not an endorsement of their work above the work of unlisted researchers.

It is also possible that the results for local level initiatives and referendums can be obtained by contacting the supervisor of elections<https://dos.elections.myflorida.com/supervisors/> from each county where those races took place.

State Archives staff will be happy to assist you further either by phone (850) 245-6719 or by email archives@dos.myflorida.com<mailto:archives@dos.myflorida.com>.

I hope this is helpful.

Ryan C. Ash
Deputy Director
Office of External Affairs
Florida Department of State
(850)245-6605
E-mail: Ryan.Ash@DOS.MyFlorida.com<mailto:Ryan.Ash@DOS.MyFlorida.com>
R.A. Gray Building
500 S. Bronough St, Tallahassee, Fl 32399

Dear Shawn Musgrave,

Pursuant to you recent FOIA request (case 17-00132-AP), I will be forwarding our final determination response via multiple emails. We have determined that some of the records contain sensitive information that requires encryption as explained below.

In an effort to better protect information that the Department of Justice (DOJ) maintains about individuals, we have implemented a tool to prevent accidental disclosures of sensitive personally identifiable information (PII). Documents that are responsive to a FOIA or Privacy Act request may contain sensitive PII. To safeguard this information, any email containing sensitive PII will be encrypted. Accordingly, you may receive an alert that that an encrypted message has been delivered to you. Should you receive such an alert, please use the attached instruction to decrypt and save the message. If you have any issues with this process, please reply with the error message received so that we may contact our service desk for support.

V/R
Jason T. Miller

Alternatively, if we do not receive confirmation of delivery or a read receipt, we will mail a copy to the address on file. Thank you.

 

V/R

Jason T. Miller

FOIA Analyst III

Freedom of Information and Privacy Act Unit

FOIA and Information Law Section

Drug Enforcement Administration

Desk: (571) 776-3436

Email: Jason.T.Miller2@dea.gov

If you have received this communication in error, please immediately delete all copies of this information and notify me by e-mail.  The use, dissemination, distribution, or reproduction of this communication by unintended recipients is not authorized and may be unlawful"

title: ALPR datasharing information - Whittier CA Police Dept

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: ALPR datasharing information - Whittier CA Police Dept
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

 Information related to Automated License Plate Reader (ALPR) data sharing. 1) The names of agencies and organizations with which the Agency shares ALPR data; 2) The names of agencies and organizations from which the Agency receives ALPR data; 3) The names of agencies and organizations with which the Agency shares “hot list” information; 4) The names of agencies and organizations from which the Agency receives “hot list” information;

*Records obtained from other agencies show the Whittier Police Department shares ALPR data with other agencies through Vigilant Solutions.  IF WPD is still a Vigilant Solutions customer, that program is capable of easily producing a report with the requested information.  

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Greg Buhl

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: MCS VK 2 4.1.24
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

A copy of body cam footage from the arrest of Vitallii Kovalev, also possibly known as Vitalii Kovalev and Vitaly Kovalev. Mr. Kovalev was arrested on June 16, 2020. His arrest number is MCSO20ARR002460 and offense number MCSO20OFF003605. The arresting officer was Ty Torres.

This footage was previously released to CBS News, and aired on its news magazine program 60 Minutes on Sunday, March 31, 2024. As this footage has already been displayed publicly by a major news network, there should be no additional concerns for releasing it to the public.

Verification of the public display of the footage can be found on 60 Minutes' YouTube channel. Please see the following link, beginning at 5:00: https://youtu.be/JdPSD1SUYCY?si=UrAQyCQvt9U4S0Tn

I am asking you waive any fees associated with this request. I am a member of the news media. My bylines, which include Unicorn Riot, Covert Action Magazine, and the Geopolitical Economy Report, can be found in both print and electronic publications. I am sending this request in coordination with Muckrock, an award-winning and nationally-recognized news organization.

This request is not being made for commercial purposes.

All documents will be provided to the general public without charge.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Robert Skvarla, Jr.

communications.subject: You have an invoice available :: S327629-022924
communications.communication:
RE:  Public Records Request#: S327629-022924 
 
Dear Chris Martin, 
 
 PAYMENT DUE 
 
The City may be the custodian of at least some of the requested public records and a payment is due to continue processing this request. Please log into the Portland Public Records Request Center to pay these fees. 
 
Fees include research time to locate and analyze the requested records, even if no records are located or if the requested records are determined to be exempt from disclosure. We will not be working on your request until we receive the payment. 
 
Please log in to the Portland Public Records Request Center (copy and right click this link to open it in your browser) and make a payment on this request. 
 
You may pay by electronic check or credit card by going to "My Public Records Request Center" and select "View My Invoices." Then scroll to find your open invoice and select "Make Payment." Follow the screen prompts to make a payment. 
 
Due to the current state of emergency, most City offices are not staffed. Consequently, if you mail a check it could delay the response time and it is preferable that you use the online payment portal to make an electronic payment. However, if you need to mail a check, please reply to this message and ask for the correct address. Please be sure and provide your Reference Number (S327629-022924) on your check. 
 
Please be advised that pursuant to ORS 192.329(3)(b) and (4)(b), your public records request will be closed if payment is not received within sixty (60) days of this invoice. 
 
 
Sincerely, 
 
 
City of Portland Public Records Responder 
 
 
 *Please note that you will need to disable your pop-up blocker on your browser's settings in order to make an online payment.
*Please see this Answer for more information:  A006257-010816 If you are having technical difficulties with the website, please contact the website administrator by phone or email.  (503) 823-6040 or prrhelp@portlandoregon.gov

communications.subject: DC Freedom of Information Act Request: Data Request for Local Ballot Initiatives/Referenda (District Of Columbia Board Of Elections)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the DC Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting data on local ballot initiatives/referenda that took place in the state since 1972. Specifically, I need the following information to be included in the data.

1. Text of the ballot initiative/referendum
2. Local government where the election took place.
3. County where the local government is located
4. Election date
5. Result of election (votes for, votes against, pass/fail)
6. Threshold to pass (50%, two-thirds, etc)

This website from California provides a good example of the type of data I am requesting:
https://data.ca.gov/dataset/election-data/resource/67e83a65-2b55-41ec-9420-b33b666d4711

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jimin Han

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

An audit log of all ALPR queries to out-of-state law enforcement agencies between 1/1/2023 and 2/18/2024. This request is not seeking the plate numbers or any personally identifiable information. It is seeking the date and time for conducting a query in the specific date range cited.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

e

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
Our ALPR system does not make queries directly to out of state law enforcement agencies. Our ALPR system is connected to the National Crime Information Center (NCIC) and the Florida Crime Information Center (FCIC). Vehicle data from these sources is uploaded into a database maintained by our ALPR vendor.


Major Johnny Greenwood
Department of Administrative Services
Putnam County Sheriff’s Office
130 Orie Griffin Blvd.
Palatka, Florida 32177
(386) 329-0820

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
Thank you.

I am seeking all queries into NCIC that were for out-of-state plates. I am not seeking the plate numbers, only when and who conducted the query.

Thank you.

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
Good morning,

I have spoken with one of our staff that has access to the FLOCK system. He advised that the tag numbers do not indicate which state they are from. It only gives the numbers on the tag. He has no way of separating Florida tags from out of state tags. You might consider reaching out to FLOCK directly to see if they can provide the specific data you are looking for. Additionally, the FLOCK reports can only be run in 30 day periods and contain every vehicle that is captured by the cameras which will be in the thousands each month. This is really not the data you are requesting and time to redact thousands of entries for each 30 day period will be extremely time consuming and costly. Since the ALPR cannot determine individual state tags, every tag both in-state and out-of-state that is captured is ran in FLOCK’s database which compares the tag number with NCIC/FCIC data.

Major Johnny Greenwood
Department of Administrative Services
Putnam County Sheriff’s Office
130 Orie Griffin Blvd.
Palatka, Florida 32177
(386) 329-0820

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
Thank you.

I'm not seeking scans by Flock. I'm seeking queries by staff. I would assume that those would not number in the thousands and there should be a record which indicates the state and purpose for the query.

Thanks.

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
I need clarification. Your original request asks for ALPR queries to out-of-state law enforcement agencies between 1/1/2023 and 2/18/2024. Now you are requesting staff queries for NCIC data. There is a possibility that I can get a number from our communications center on how many requests we have made to NCIC/FCIC during that time period. This will however have nothing to do with the ALPR cameras.

I am sure we are not the only agency you have requested this from. Can you provide some type of sample that you have received from another entity so I can understand what you are looking for?

Major Johnny Greenwood
Department of Administrative Services
Putnam County Sheriff’s Office
130 Orie Griffin Blvd.
Palatka, Florida 32177
(386) 329-0820

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
I have received an exported log with data from the specified parameters from Vigilant's system.

Thanks.

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Sunshine Law Request: ALPR Log
communications.communication:
We use Flock cameras not Vigilant cameras and have been told we have no means of gathering that information. If you have obtained this data from Flock I would like to see it so I can figure out how it was obtained.

Major Johnny Greenwood
Department of Administrative Services
Putnam County Sheriff’s Office
130 Orie Griffin Blvd.
Palatka, Florida 32177
(386) 329-0820

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Crime data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Data on incidents/crimes reported from 1/1/2009 through 12/31/2020. I am part of a public health research team that is seeking this information for research aimed at reducing violence. We already received data from you on incidents/crimes reported from 1/1/2009 through 12/31/2020 and want to extend our analyses into 2021-2023.

Specifically we are looking for data on all incidents that fall under FBI UCR Part I and Part II [https://ucr.fbi.gov/crime-in-the-u.s/2011/crime-in-the-u.s.-2011/offense-definitions], including as many of the following fields as possible (based on the FBI UCR data elements shown at [https://www.fbi.gov/file-repository/ucr/ucr-2019-1-nibrs-technical-specification.pdf/view]):

Incident Number (UCR Data Element 2)
Incident Date & Time/Hour (UCR Data Element 3)
UCR Offense Code (UCR Data Element 6)
Offense Attempted/Completed (UCR Data Element 7)
Offender Suspected of Using (UCR Data Element 8)
Bias Motivation (UCR Data Element 8A)
Location Type (UCR Data Element 9)
Type Weapon/Force Involved (UCR Data Element 13)
Type Property Loss/Etc. (UCR Data Element 14)
Suspected Drug Type (UCR Data Element 20)
Type of Victim (UCR Data Element 25)
Type of Officer Activity/Circumstance (UCR Data Element 25A)
Officer Assignment Type (UCR Data Element 25B)
Officer- ORI Other Jurisdiction (UCR Data Element 25C)
Age of Victim (UCR Data Element 26)
Sex of Victim (UCR Data Element 27)
Race of Victim (UCR Data Element 28)
Ethnicity of Victim (UCR Data Element 29)
Resident Status of Victim (UCR Data Element 30)
Aggravated Assault/Homicide Circumstances (UCR Data Element 31)
Type Injury (UCR Data Element 33)
Age of Offender (UCR Data Element 37)
Sex of Offender (UCR Data Element 38)
Race of Offender (UCR Data Element 39)
Ethnicity of Offender (UCR Data Element 39A)
Arrest Date (UCR Data Element 42)
Type of Arrest (UCR Data Element 43)
UCR Arrest Offense Code (UCR Data Element 43)
Age of Arrestee (UCR Data Element 47)
Sex of Arrestee (UCR Data Element 48)
Race of Arrestee (UCR Data Element 49)
Ethnicity of Arrestee (UCR Data Element 50)
Resident Status of Arrestee (UCR Data Element 51)
Disposition of Arrestee Under 18 (UCR Data Element 52)

and

street level location data for each incident, such as a geocoded location, street address, census block and/or census block group

We are requesting this data in a machine-readable format such as Excel spreadsheets or .csv files.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Christina Mair

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act Request: Jose Mena - Records
communications.communication:
Aloha:  The request is for:

1. The full and complete content of every internal investigative file in which Jose Alexander Mena was the named officer, along with associated metadata.
2. Training record for Jose Alexander Mena

For #1, No disclosure.  Disclosure of any records within this description would constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  See Section 92F-13, Hawaii Revised Statutes (HRS).  In addition, the privacy interest of the individual outweighs any public interest in disclosure.  See Section 92F-14, HRS.  There are no exceptions for disclosure.  See also section 92F-12, HRS.

For #2, please find attached the training record for Jose Alexander Mena.

Mahalo.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Request: Mira Slovak
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to or mentioning Mira Slovak, listed by the FBI's RIDS Dead List as dying on 6/16/2014 nad having been an anti-Communist Czech defector to the U.S. Per FBI standards and regulations, an FBI file is acceptable proof of death.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the ELSUR Records System, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records (as the Bureau has posted copies of records that it previously said were transferred to NARA such as the Tokyo Rose file).

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such. I have previously written about the government and its activities for AND Magazine, MuckRock and Glomar Disclosure and have an open arrangement with each. My articles have been widely read, with some reaching over 100,000 readers. As such, as I have a reasonable expectation of publication and my editorial and writing skills are well established. In addition, I discuss and comment on the files online and make them available through the non-profit Internet Archive, disseminating them to a large audience. While my research is not limited to this, a great deal of it, including this, focuses on the activities and attitudes of the government itself. As such, it is not necessary for me to demonstrate the relevance of this particular subject in advance. Additionally, case law states that “proof of the ability to disseminate the released information to a broad cross-section of the public is not required.” Judicial Watch, Inc. v. Dep’t of Justice, 365 F.3d 1108, 1126 (D.C. Cir. 2004); see Carney v. U.S. Dep’t of Justice, 19 F.3d 807, 814-15 (2d Cir. 1994). Further, courts have held that "qualified because it also had “firm” plans to “publish a number of . . . ‘document sets’” concerning United States foreign and national security policy." Under this criteria, as well, I qualify as a member of the news media. Additionally, courts have held that the news media status "focuses on the nature of the requester, not its request. The provision requires that the request be “made by” a representative of the news media. Id. § 552(a)(4)(A)(ii)(II). A newspaper reporter, for example, is a representative of the news media regardless of how much interest there is in the story for which he or she is requesting information." As such, the details of the request itself are moot for the purposes of determining the appropriate fee category. As such, my primary purpose is to inform about government activities by reporting on it and making the raw data available and I therefore request that fees be waived. Per DOJ FOIA guidance, "a requester should be granted a fee waiver if the requested information (1) sheds light on the activities and operations of the government; (2) is likely to contribute significantly to public understanding of those operations and activities; and (3) is not primarily in the commercial interest of the requester." As this FOIA meets all of those requirements (see above), a fee waiver is warranted.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.


Sincerely,

Michael Best

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Request: Mira Slovak
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Best,

The FBI has received your Freedom of Information Act/Privacy (FOIPA) request and it will be forwarded to Initial Processing for review.   Your request will be processed under the provisions of FOIPA and a response will be mailed to you at a later date.

Requests for fee waivers and expedited processing will be addressed once your request has been assigned an FOIPA request number. You will receive written notification of the FBI’s decision.

Please be advised, beginning Wednesday, March 1, 2017, you will no longer be able to submit FOIPA requests via email.  On this date, FOIPARequest@ic.fbi.gov<mailto:FOIPARequest@ic.fbi.gov> will permanently be taken offline and requests will need to be submitted using the FBI’s electronic FOIPA portal at http://efoia.fbi.gov.  Alternatively, you may submit your request using fax or standard mail.

Information regarding the Freedom of Information Act/Privacy is available at http://www.fbi.gov<http://www.fbi.gov>/ or http://www.fbi.gov/foia/<http://www.fbi.goiv/foia/>.  If you require additional assistance please contact the Public Information Officer.

Thank you,

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents). communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: ALPR purchases - City of Whittier
communications.communication:
Hello:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any invoices, purchase orders, or contracts related to the purchase of automated license plate readers (ALPRs) or subscriptions of ALPR related services.

title: University of Houston - Shahzia Sikander "Satanic" displays

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: University of Houston - Shahzia Sikander "Satanic" displays
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. Any Public Information Act requests concerning the Shahzia Sikander works, as well as any communications to or from the requestor concerning the request, and any records produced in response to the request.

2. Any agreements concerning the acquisition, display, or other use of any of the Sikander works.

3. Any records concerning the decision to cancel or postpone the February 28, 2024, program concerning the works, including (but not limited to) any records relating to the unavailability of the artist.

4. Any communications to or from any elected official and the University of Houston concerning the Sikander works.

5. Any communications to or from any member of the Board of Regents concerning the Sikadner works.

Please note that this request does not seek a search of records held by faculty or students.

Please also note that this request seeks public records wherever they may be found, including on devices or networks owned or operated by private parties. For example, if an employee uses a personal cell phone or social media account to conduct public business, records created, maintained, or held on the phone or account are public records subject to this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Bethel School District – Request for a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by the District including District Responses for the years 2010 - 2021
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

I request a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by Bethel School District and a complete electronic copy of the District's Responses to these Public Records Requests for the time period January 1, 2010 through November 4, 2021.

In the event the District chooses to provide these records in installments over time I request the records to be produced in reverse chronological order - from the most recent records to the earliest.

If this request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the PRA. I also request a detailed contemporaneous log to be provided for any document withheld or redacted.

For each responsive record the District contends is exempt from public disclosure, in whole or in part, please specifically identify the record by subject, title, author, custodian and date, and state how a specific statutory exemption applies to each record as required by RCW 42.56.210(3) and Rental Housing Ass'n v. Des Moines, 165 Wn.2d 525, 199 P.3d 393 (2009).

I request electronic production of all electronic records in the original NATIVE electronic format for each record. 

I request for these public records to be produced by public (no password) e-mail attachment or link. If electronic attachment or link is not possible, an alternative would be to produce responsive records via USB DRIVE or DATA CD-ROM.

THIS REQUEST IS NOT BEING MADE FOR COMMERCIAL PURPOSES.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. 

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

PRA Audit

VIA EMAIL TO: communications@bethelsd.org

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

I request a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by Bethel School District and a complete electronic copy of the District's Responses to these Public Records Requests for the time period January 1, 2010 through May 29, 2023.

In the event the District chooses to provide these records in installments over time I request the records to be produced in reverse chronological order - from the most recent records to the earliest.

If this request is denied in whole or part, I ask that you justify all deletions by reference to specific exemptions of the PRA. I also request a detailed contemporaneous log to be provided for any document withheld or redacted.

For each responsive record the District contends is exempt from public disclosure, in whole or in part, please specifically identify the record by subject, title, author, custodian and date, and state how a specific statutory exemption applies to each record as required by RCW 42.56.210(3) and Rental Housing Ass'n v. Des Moines, 165 Wn.2d 525, 199 P.3d 393 (2009).

I request electronic production of all electronic records in the original NATIVE electronic format for each record.

I request for these public records to be produced by public (no password) e-mail attachment or link. If electronic attachment or link is not possible, an alternative would be to produce responsive records via USB DRIVE or DATA CD-ROM.

THIS REQUEST IS NOT BEING MADE FOR COMMERCIAL PURPOSES.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

PRA Audit

I don't understand your "communication informing you of our need for an
extension" including "clarification."

Here is the original request:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

I request a complete electronic copy of all Public Records Requests received by Bethel School District and a complete electronic copy of the District's Responses to these Public Records Requests for the time period January 1, 2010 through November 4, 2021.

if not,

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Iowa Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

All emails sent by Beth Goetz, Kirk Ferentz and Brian Ferentz between Oct. 20, 2023 and Nov. 1, 2023.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Ben Welsh

communications.subject: Your public records request
communications.communication:
Hello Ben,

Your faxed public records request, copy attached, was forwarded to me to process.

I wanted to reach out to clarify the scope of your request. Are there specific words/terms that should be searched, or is there a particular subject matter you are interested in? Even with the fairly narrow date range, the search could produce a number of records pertaining to a variety of subjects, and the responsive records will have to be reviewed individually for any confidential information that may be exempt from disclosure based on Iowa Code Chapter 22. In accordance with our fee schedule<https://transparency.uiowa.edu/faqs/public-records-fee-schedule>, we charge a rate of $30/hour, with one hour free, for the time to retrieve, review, and redact records. Please also note that we are processing a high volume of other requests at the moment, and requests for emails generally take longer for us to complete, due to the legal review required.

Please also be aware that if the search produces any records pertaining to personnel matters, those would likely be exempt from disclosure based on Iowa Code 22.7(11) (confidential personnel records).

Please let me know if you would like to narrow the scope of your request, or if you want to proceed with your request as written. I will be in touch to let you know if there will be costs for the retrieval/review.

Thanks,
Aubree


Aubree Johnson
Public Records Officer
The University of Iowa
351 Plaza Centre One
Iowa City, IA 52242
public-records@uiowa.edu<mailto:public-records@uiowa.edu>

NOTICE TO RECIPIENT: THIS MESSAGE AND ANY RESPONSE TO IT MAY CONSTITUTE A PUBLIC RECORD, AND THEREFORE, MAY BE AVAILABLE UPON REQUEST IN ACCORDANCE WITH IOWA PUBLIC RECORDS LAW, IOWA CODE CHAPTER 22.

communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: R001734-032124
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 

 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST updated 03/29/2024, Request # R001734-032124. 
Dear Jessica Cabrera, 
Your request contains the phrase "any and all".  The use of that phrase can be intended to be very broad therefore, the University denies your request because it is not a proper request under the Nevada Public Records Act (the “Act”). 
The University’s obligation is to produce public records for inspection or copying upon receipt of a request that “is sufficient to identify the record.” Nevada Revised Statutes (NRS) 239.863(c).  In addressing this issue, courts have held that “agencies are required to disclose only ‘identifiable’ governmental records not otherwise exempt;” “the request to the agency must itself be focused and specific.” Rogers v. Superior Court, 19 Cal. App.4th 469, 481 (1993). “Wholesale requests for general information to be analyzed, collected and compiled by the responding government entity are not encompassed therein.” Hodai v. City of Tucson, C20141225 (Ariz. Super. Ct. 2014) citing mag Entertainment LLC v. Div. of Alcohol Beverages Control, 868 A.2d 1067. 1076 (N.J. Sup. Ct., App. Div. 2005).  A government agency is not required to respond to an overly broad request that does not seek specific records.  Id. at 1074, citing Capitol Info. Assoc. v. Ann Arbor Police, 360 N.W.2d 262, 263 (1985). 
In regards to your request for those who have completed Title IX training for the academic year of 2023-2024, the University does not maintain records as requested.  Training takes place within 6 months of hire and then every two years thereafter.  See NSHE Handbook, Title 4, Chapter 8, Section 14(A)(2)(b). 
However, UNLV can report that as of March 26, 2024, 7,296 employees have completed training. If you have any questions, please contact publicrecords@unlv.edu and include the reference number in the subject line. Your request is complete and closed. Please do not reply to this message, as closed requests are not actively monitored. 
Sincerely, 
Office of Public Affairs 
University of Nevada, Las Vegas

--- Please respond above this line --- 

 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST updated 03/29/2024, Request # R001733-032124. 
Dear Jessica Cabrera, 
The University of Nevada, Las Vegas (UNLV) denies your request for Title IX complaints, as such records, if any, are deemed confidential and exempt from disclosure.  See Nevada System of Higher Education (NSHE) Code, Title 2, Chapter 5, Section 5.6.2(c)(d)(e); Nevada Administrative Code (NAC) 284.718; Family Educational Rights and Privacy Act (FERPA) 20 U.S.C. §1232g, 34 CFR Part 99, Nev. Rev. Stat. (NRS) 396.535; and Donrey v. Bradshaw, 106 Nev. 630 (1990) (privacy, safety, and the release of such records could chill the reporting of such incidents). 
UNLV relies, in good faith, on this claim of confidentiality to refuse to disclose the requested documents, if any. NRS 239.0107(d)(2); NRS 239.012. However, the University has searched its record and can provide the total number of Title IX complaints filed for those years. See below: Number of formal Title IX complaints: 
2021-2022: 1 
2022-2023: 
2023-2024: 1
"1/1/2024 - 3/21/2024: 0
Your request is complete and closed. Please do not reply to this message, as closed requests are not actively monitored.  If you have any questions, please contact publicrecords@unlv.edu and include the reference number in the subject line. 

Sincerely,

Office of Public Affairs
University of Nevada, Las Vegas"

communications.communication:

All teaching materials used by the St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department to train officers on the deployment of, and recovery from, common chemical munitions (including skunk, OC, CS, PAVA, HC, pepper spray, or 'tear gas' in general). The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

communications.subject: SLMPD - Public Records Request :: P002741-012824
communications.communication:
Dear Lynne Peskoe-Yang: 
Thank you for submitting a records request to the St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department.  Your request was given reference number P002741-012824, for tracking purposes. Type of Records Selected: Other Police Record Complaint Number (if applicable): Type of Incident (if applicable): Description of Request (if applicable):   To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the The Missouri Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

All teaching materials used by the St. Louis Metropolitan Police Department to train officers on the deployment of, and recovery from, common chemical munitions (including skunk, OC, CS, PAVA, HC, pepper spray, or 'tear gas' in general). Please also include, with course teaching materials, materials provided by external agencies that sponsor, teach, or provide teaching materials for a particular course, including but not limited to safety data sheets provided by equipment manufacturers and training worksheets compiled by non-SLPD personnel.

The requester is a journalist who will share information with the public—as such, kindly waive any fees if possible.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Lynne Peskoe-Yang

Upload documents directly: https://accounts.muckrock.com/accounts/login/?next=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.muckrock.com%2Faccounts%2Flogin%2F%3Fnext%3D%252Faccounts%252Fagency_login%252Fst-louis-metropolitan-police-department-671%252Fst-louis-police-training-curriculum-chemical-munitions-157859%252F%253F&url_auth_token=AAAj9WsQ4FuNTZD2Y9DnVAucV28%3A1rUH23%3AId6x0DJmmqCevf8pyJGOlnH0p7kvmhgKiNkkNqPxpzs 
We are currently reviewing your request and will contact you if any additional information is required.  Otherwise, we will proceed with locating and gathering responsive records from various departments.  Once records are located, they will need to be reviewed to determine what may be released at this time.  All records are released in accordance with the Missouri Sunshine Law, Chapter 610 and SLMPD Policy. 
There will be a cost associated with this request, and you will be contacted with more details prior to records being released.  The earliest records are typically available is as follows: 
• Arrest Reports, Background Checks, Crash Reports, Police Calls for Service, Law Enforcement Requests and Non-criminal Police Reports are available within 10 days of submission of your request. 
• Criminal Police Reports, evidentiary material and other non-standard requests are available within 30 days of submission. 
In the event your request will require additional time you will be provided with a detailed explanation of any further delay. 
 
You can monitor the progress of your request at the link below and you'll receive an email when your request has been completed. 
 
Thank you!

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Legion of Doom
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Files mentioning the Legion of Doom, a hacker group active from the 1980s to the late 1990s and early 2000. During its heyday from around 1984-1991 Legion of Doom was widely considered to be the most capable hacking group in the world. To this day, LOD ranks as one of the most influential hacking groups in the history of technology.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Emma Best
